Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) performs a convolution operation on an image using filters (kernels).
The calculation’s main purpose is:

Purpose of This Calculation

The CNN uses these calculations to detect important features from an image, such as:

Edges
Shapes
Textures
Patterns
Object parts

This is how CNN “understands” images before classification.

What Happens in This Image?

The image has 3 channels:

Red Channel
Green Channel
Blue Channel (RGB)

Each channel has:

Input pixel values
A small filter/kernel (3×3 matrix)

The CNN performs:

Multiply input values with kernel values
Add all results
Add bias
Produce one output value
Example from the Image

For Red Channel:

Input values × Kernel values
→ Result = 314

=========
Input values × Kernel values
→ Result = 314, how it is came

For the Red Channel, the CNN calculates 314 using:

=======

Step 1: Input Matrix (Red Channel)
| 155  156  158 |
| 154  157  159 |
| 151  155  158 |


Step 2: Kernel Matrix
| -1  -1   1 |
|  0   1  -1 |
|  0   1   1 |

Step 3: Element-wise Multiplication
| 155×(-1)   156×(-1)   158×1  |
| 154×0      157×1      159×(-1) |
| 151×0      155×1      158×1 |

Step 4: Result After Multiplication
| -155   -156    158 |
|   0     157   -159 |
|   0     155    158 |

Step 5: Add All Values
-155 + (-156) + 158 + 0 + 157 + (-159) + 0 + 155 + 158
= 314

Final Output
Red Channel Output = 314

=======

This process is called:

Convolution Operation

The filter slides over the image and performs:

Multiplication
Addition

to extract features from the image.
=========

